  "prompt": "Why does Ben Affleck\u2019s Batman Kill people intentionally?",
  "response": "In Zack Snyder's Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice, Ben Affleck's Batman is portrayed as a more brutal and violent version of the character compared to previous cinematic interpretations. He kills criminals both intentionally and seemingly without much remorse. This approach was a deliberate creative choice by Snyder to present a darker, more traumatized version of Batman.\n\nThis Batman is older and more cynical, having experienced significant personal tragedy (implied loss of Robin and years of fighting crime in Gotham). The character appears to have become disillusioned and more willing to use lethal force, which is a departure from the traditional Batman comic book ethics of not killing.\n\nWhile controversial among fans, Snyder argued that this version of Batman represents a Batman who has been worn down by years of fighting crime and has become more pragmatic about eliminating threats. The characterization suggests a Batman who believes that some criminals are beyond redemption and that killing them is sometimes necessary to protect innocent people.\n\nIt's worth noting that this interpretation is not universally accepted by Batman fans and differs significantly from most comic book and animated portrayals of the character, where Batman has a strict moral code against killing.",
